narratives.question_text: How would you summarize ECON 110 05 for a fellow student? Would you recommend ECON 110 05 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: I think this was a great course. It offered a strong reading list and presented the intersection of AI and philosophy quite well. Though the readings were at times dense or very specialized, the lectures did a good job of distilling the important information. I happen to be quite interested in this topic, personally, and found the class captivating. As a writing credit, the work load was quite reasonable, though the prompts often left too much room for interpretation (which became a problem if you answered a question that McDermott wasn't looking for). I would have liked to see a little more class discussion early on, rather than 75 minutes of straight lecture. As the semester progressed, we did get a chance to debate more of the counter-intuitive topics, which I appreciated.
Interesting philosophical discussion, but do not take if you are looking for an AI class. It's great at what it is.
Great 400-level elective for engineering / CS majors who also need a writing credit. Two papers and a ton of optional reading.
